WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

NOTE
Full voiceover captions for product-tour-main.mp4.
Re-time cues to match your final edit. Assumes ~2:50–3:00 master cut.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.500
Retrieval-augmented generation
shouldn't mean stitching a dozen tools by hand.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.500
<b>Unified RAG Studio</b> is a single workspace:
walk <b>seventeen</b> guided stages in the Designer,

00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:14.000
or start from your documents in <b>Autopilot</b> —

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
then evaluate, harden, and export
what you actually ship.

00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:22.000
Two front doors.
Same truth under the hood.

00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:30.000
<b>Designer</b> is for explicit control — cloud through vector store,
query processing and retrieval, context compression and reranking,
generation and routing, memory, evaluation, observability and tools,
<b>guardrails</b>, human-in-the-loop, and a final <b>review</b>.

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:38.000
<b>Autopilot</b> is for running optimisation passes over your corpus
when you want the system to propose a strong baseline.

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:45.000
You're not hunting for the next file to edit —
the <b>stage rail</b> is the contract.

00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:56.000
Configure cloud and ingestion, shape chunks, pick embeddings
and the vector store, optionally tune query processing, then tighten retrieval.

00:00:56.500 --> 00:01:15.000
As you move forward, the UI and cost estimates update
so you catch bad pairings <b>before</b> you export.

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:20.000
Production RAG isn't only accuracy —
it's <b>what you allow through</b>.

00:01:20.500 --> 00:01:30.000
<b>Guardrails</b> let you set input and output policies
so safety rides with the orchestration layer.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:38.000
<b>Human in the Loop</b> is its own stage when you need explicit human gates.

00:01:38.500 --> 00:01:46.000
When you'd rather iterate from real files,
<b>Autopilot</b> runs structured passes —

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:54.000
chunking, embeddings, retrieval, <b>evaluation</b> —
and you get something you can inspect and edit back in Designer.

00:01:54.500 --> 00:02:05.000
Treat it as a smart draft.
Not a black box.

00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:10.000
Before you freeze the config,
you want receipts:

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:18.000
what retrieved, with what scores, how fast.
Tweak retrieval or chunking, rerun,

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:28.000
and decide with data — not vibes.

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:33.000
When the pipeline is grounded,
export the artifacts your team expects —

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:40.000
<b>Python, YAML, Terraform, Compose, Kubernetes</b> —
and wire into deployment.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Operational signals live where you
already run the stack.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:50.000
If you're done duct-taping RAG pipelines,
open <b>Unified RAG Studio</b>.

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:55.000
Walk the seventeen stages —
or let Autopilot draft your first-pass config.

00:02:55.500 --> 00:03:00.000
Start free, or book a walkthrough —
we'll meet you where you ship.
